SIMPLE: weld
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weld
<hw>Weld</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧ld)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wield.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weld</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weld
<hw>Weld</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧ld)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>welde</ets>; akin to Scot. <ets>wald</ets>, Prov. G.
<ets>waude</ets>, G. <ets>wau</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>vau</ets>, D.
<ets>wouw</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An herb (<spn>Reseda
luteola</spn>) related to mignonette, growing in Europe, and to some
extent in America; dyer's broom; dyer's rocket; dyer's weed; wild woad.
It is used by dyers to give a yellow color.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>woald</asp>, <asp>wold</asp>, and <asp>would</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Coloring matter or dye extracted from this
plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weld</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Weld
<hw>Weld</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Welded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Welding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably originally the same
word as <ets>well</ets> to spring up, to gush; perhaps from the Scand.;
cf. Sw. <ets>v⟦aum⟧lla</ets> to weld, <ets>uppv⟦aum⟧lla</ets> to boil
up, to spring up, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧lde</ets> to gush, G. <ets>wellen</ets>
to weld. See <er>Well</er> to spring.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To press or beat into intimate and permanent union,
as two pieces of iron when heated almost to fusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Very few of the metals, besides iron and platinum. are
capable of being welded. Horn and tortoise shell possess this useful
property.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To unite closely or intimately.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two women faster <qex>welded</qex> in one love.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weld</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Weld
<hw>Weld</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being welded; the joint
made by welding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Butt weld</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Butt</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Scarf weld</b></col>, <cd>a joint made by overlapping, and
welding together, the scarfed ends of two pieces.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weldable</ent>⟦br⟧
